illed and overcrowded place that sought to treat the body and reform the soul.Using the sole surviving admissions book for Toledo, Spain’s Hospital de Santiago, Cristian Berco reconstructs the lives of men and women afflicted with the pox by tracing their experiences before, during, and after their hospitalization. Through an innovative combination of medical, institutional, and notarial sources, he explores the physical and social lives of the patients. What were the social repercussions of living with a shameful disease? What did living with this chronic illness mean for careers and networks, love and families, and everyday relationships? From Body to Community is a textured analysis at once touched by the illness but not solely defined by it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDiseasesxSocial aspectszSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aSexually transmitted diseasesxHospitalszSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aSexually transmitted diseasesxPatientszSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aSexually transmitted diseasesxTreatmentzSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aSexually transmitted diseaseszSpainxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262068140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442620681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442620681.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles